There is something bad about a mother being &quot;obsessed&quot;
with the safety and interests of her child - and
consistently putting his needs before her own? After
all, if we ignore Lazarus' (and on one occasion
Ford's) opinions and just look at the record, what do
we actually _know_ about the Johnsons?

1) When they are being rescued from the concentration
camp, and Eleanor fears they may not all get onto the
ship, she plans to pass Hubert through the crowd so
that he gets on even if she doesn't. IOW she is ready
to lose her son forever rather than let him come to
harm, an attitude I should expect Heinlein (never mind
King Solomon) to entirely approve.

2) On board ship, Eleanor keeps a close eye on
Hubert's education, teaching whichever class he
happens to be in at the time.  Assuming she is not in
a position to simply educate him at home (an obvious
course now but less common whan MC was written) this
would seem a reasonable option if feasible.

3) On the Jockaira planet, Hubert screams for help
when picked up (uninvited and apparently without
warning) by an eight-foot alien creature - a perfectly
reasonable reaction (the alien's intentions may have
been quite innocent, but Hubert doesn't know that) and
indeed what millions of children are _taught_ to do if
grabbed by a stranger - and Eleanor goes to his aid.
Whereupon, Ford promptly turns on Eleanor and accuses
her of having &quot;spoiled the boy rotten&quot; and of
endangering the colony, all without the slightest
evidence, or any explanation of what Hubert is
supposed to have done wrong.

(Subsequently, the Jockaira insist on taking &quot;custody&quot;
of all the telepathic sensitives, as a result  of
which most of them go insane. Shortly after _this_,
Ford himself goes into temporary insanity after
entering a Jockaira Temple. All in all, Hubert's fear
of the unknown, even if mistaken in that specific
instance, seems to have been a good deal more
justified than Ford's dismissal of it).

4) When the Families decide to return to Earth, the
Johnsons are divided. Eleanor, presumably remembering
the circumstances of their departure, wishes to stay
behing, but Hubert (now eighteen or a bit over) goes
along with the majority, even though it may cost him
his life and will almost certainly mean lifelong
separation from his only living relative.  Lazarus
shows not the slightest sympathy for his problem, just
impatiently telling him to get on with it - though a
pause for thought over such a momentous and
irreversible decision (far graver than any _I_ ever
had to make at Hubert's age) would seem both right and
natural.

5) When she realises what Hubert has done, Eleanor
falls in with his decision and also returns to Earth -
an act akin to a Jewish woman (dare I say &quot;a Jewish
mother&quot;?) following her son back to Germany, though
both are totally ignorant of conditions there, and for
all they know the &quot;Nazis&quot; may still be in power. If
Earth is still hostile, this could easily mean death
for both of them. Yet Eleanor, who could remain in
perfect safety where she is, instead goes back to face
her worst nighmare rather than risk leaving Hubert to
die alone. Her son's decision may prove fatal, but if
so she will take her chances with him rather than
abandon him. She has, so to speak, come full circle,
and on this last appearence, as in the beginning, we
see her putting Hubert first. Yet Lazarus reports her
arrival totally without comment, giving not the
slightest thought to what it must have cost her.

[In the end, of course, all this proves academic. By
decree of the author, Earth is no longer dangerous,
and they can &quot;all live happily ever after&quot;, insofar as
humans ever do.  But neither Hubert nor Eleanor (or
indeed anyone else) could possibly have known that in
advance. For all they know, the decision to return may
well be fatal. Whatever the Johnsons' faults, lack of
courage is plainly not among them].

All in all,  though no doubt as imperfect as the rest
of us, Eleanor and Hubert seem to me quite good people
with at least as many virtues as vices - maybe more.
To my mind,  Lazarus' [1] dismissive attitude toward
them richly invites a boot up the backside.

[1]  I omit Ford, because his later experiences _may_
have caused him to modify his attirude. Afaik we
aren't told, but I give him the benefit of the doubt.

