I probably agree about the omission. The Eleanor Johnson interludes seem
to have displayed a stray bee buzzing in Heinlein's bonnet whilst he
wrote _Methuselah's Children_, not truly essential to the story, used as
if it were an ornament to the structure of the overall tale, a filigree
or pattern in the finished tile, perhaps pleasing to some, distracting
to others, just as he used interjections such as those about supposed
current affairs (the &quot;silly season&quot; news items in SiaSL or Friday or,
more integral to the story, in &quot;Jackpot&quot;). It could be omitted without
doing great violence to theme or plot or color. It does, however, offer
a portrait in the development or lack of development of character
affected by stress and pressure. Whether that's essential I'll leave to
another.

