About Eleanor, we don't know enough, but we have hints enough to
conclude from what we see of her at the outset that she is immature (&quot;In
all her twenty-seven years ...&quot;), self-centered (&quot;her cherished first
home of her own with its ... thermostat which she could set to the
temperature she liked without consulting others&quot;), over-reacting to
stress (&quot;She herself had wept&quot;), and somewhat irrational (&quot;could anyone
be so wicked, so terribly wicked as to want to kill anyone as harmless
and helpless as herself and her baby&quot;), although a sympathetic object of
our pity, whether or not we indeed sympathize with her overwrought
fears.

I have to point out here that &quot;Ain't nuthin' really happened to her yet,
'cept she's got a little wet.&quot;

For comparison's sake, think about twenty-one-year-old Betty Zane with
that crucial keg of gunpowder clutched in a tablecloth over her shoulder
running twice, at first easily and apparently calmly and then faster as
they discerned the nature of her burden on her return and began firing
at her, through the war party of 600 British ranger and Shawnee savages
between her brother's blockhouse cabin and and the palisade of Ft.
Patrick Henry on today's site of Wheeling, West Virginia, in what was
probably the last battle of the American Revolution in September 1782.
See, Cptrs. 13 and 14 of Zane Gray's historical novel about the heroism
of his great-grandmother, _Betty Zane_, in which a party of 42 settlers,
men, women, and children, half of whom were killed in the attack, held
out until reinforcements arrived. http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/1261
(_Betty Zane_ was the first book of my own that I read. My grandmother
gave it to me on my fifth Christmas in 1947, along with three
others--Robinson Crusoe, Black Beauty, and a biography of J. Edgar
Hoover. It was self-published by Gray in 1903, and became very popular,
leading to his own great popularity as a writer of American romances of
the western settlement of the United States.)

Eleanor Johnson, by contrast, is subject to panic terrors. Without
sufficient reason she comes close to crushing her own child. She reacts
to being steadied by an observer who observes she's obviously panicking
by formulating an irrational plan. Good God! She's going to pass her
infant over the heads of the crowd hoping they'll continue to pass the
child into the ship. Does she have rocks in her head? Someone,
distracted, is very likely to let the child fall and be crushed
underfoot before it gets fifteen feet. She's under a heavy burden, but
for a twenty-seven-year-old woman she lacks good sense and stability to
an amazing degree.

